      "target": {
        "kind": "pull_request",
        "title": "fix(harness): avoid default Codex pre-tool loop relay",
        "body": "## Summary\n\nAdds a conservative opt-out for unnecessary Codex Harness native PreToolUse loop-detection relay subprocesses.\n\n`tools.loopDetection.enabled=false` already disables the whole loop-detection surface, including post-compaction guard behavior. That is too broad when the goal is only to reduce Codex Harness hook subprocess CPU. This PR adds a narrower config:\n\n```json5\n{\n  tools: {\n    loopDetection: {\n      nativePreToolUseRelay: false,\n    },\n  },\n}\n```\n\nDefault behavior is preserved: when this new field is unset, Codex Harness keeps the existing native PreToolUse relay behavior unless `tools.loopDetection.enabled` is explicitly `false`.\n\n## Why CPU was higher\n\nCodex Harness bridges Codex native hook callbacks into OpenClaw through command hooks. For PreToolUse, Codex invokes an `openclaw hooks relay` subprocess before tool execution so OpenClaw can run policy / loop-detection checks. On tool-heavy Codex Harness runs this creates repeated short-lived OpenClaw CLI processes (`openclaw-cli` / `openclaw-hooks`). Codex ACP does not use this same native-hook relay path, which explains part of the Harness-vs-ACP CPU delta.\n\n## Config behavior\n\n- `tools.loopDetection.enabled=false`\n  - Disables the broader loop-detection surface.\n  - Also prevents native PreToolUse relay work for loop detection.\n  - More invasive because it also disables protections tied to the master loop-detection switch.\n\n- `tools.loopDetection.nativePreToolUseRelay=false`\n  - Only stops native harnesses such as Codex Harness from installing PreToolUse relay subprocesses for loop-detection checks.\n  - Does not disable explicit `before_tool_call` policy / trusted policy relay work.\n  - Does not require changing the broader loop-detection master switch.\n  - Recommended when the issue is Codex Harness CPU from native hook relay subprocesses.\n\n- `tools.loopDetection.nativePreToolUseRelay=true` or unset\n  - Keeps current behavior for compatibility.\n\n## Evidence\n\nOpenClaw 2026.5.28 CPU probe, same Codex Harness leaf, same prompt/model/runtime, 60s window, corrected sampler excluding sampler/ps overhead:\n\n| Run | tick CPU-s | pcpu integral CPU-s | OpenClaw CLI CPU-s | OpenClaw hooks CPU-s | OpenClaw agent CPU-s |\n| --- | ---: | ---: | ---: | ---: | ---: |\n| Harness default | 9.25 | 26.320 | 3.16 | 0.44 | 3.96 |\n| Harness with `tools.loopDetection.enabled=false` | 6.82 | 23.488 | 1.07 | 0.00 | 3.88 |\n\nInterpretation:\n\n- Disabling the loop-detection relay path removed visible `openclaw-hooks` relay samples and reduced `openclaw-cli` CPU by about 66% in this 60s probe.\n- The persistent `openclaw-agent` CPU did not materially change, so this patch targets the avoidable native-hook relay subprocess work, not the Harness agent wait-loop baseline.\n- The PR implements the narrower opt-out rather than changing default behavior.\n\n## Validation\n\nClean PR head: `802ae2ed`.\n\n- PR surface: 1 commit; harness relay logic/tests plus config schema/help/docs.\n- `pnpm exec vitest run src/agents/harness/native-hook-relay.test.ts src/config/zod-schema.post-compaction-guard.test.ts src/config/schema.help.quality.test.ts` -> 4 files passed, 183 tests passed.\n- `pnpm exec vitest run src/agents/harness/native-hook-relay.test.ts extensions/codex/src/app-server/run-attempt.turn-watches.test.ts` -> 3 files passed, 218 tests passed.\n- `git diff --check` -> passed.\n",
        "branch": "fix/codex-harness-loop-detection-relay-default",
